photo.description: Ex libris Principissa[e] Piccolominia[e] Sclacoverdensis Bibliotheca[e] Scholarum Piarum. This inscription records Maria Benigna Francisca Piccolomini's gift of this book to the Piarist college in Schlackenwerth (now Ostrov, Czech Republic). Maria Benigna Francisca of Saxony, Angria and Westphalia was the daughter of Julius Henry of Saxe-Lauenburg (1586-1665) and wife of Ottavio Piccolomini-Pieri, duca d’Amalfi (1599-1656). This book comes from the Troilo Piccolomini Library, formed originally by her father. Cf. her entry in Wikipedia. Piccolomini's library was given to the Piarist college in Schlackenwerth (now Ostrov, Czech Republic), founded in 1666 and disbanded in 1876. Cf. W. Sommer, Kurze Geschichte der Stadt Schlackenwerth in Verbindung mit dem Piaristen-Collegium (Schlackenwerth, 1866). According to this entry in the Yale Law Library Rare Books Blog, "[m]ajor donations to the library included the collection of Princess Maria Piccolomini." Her father, Julius Henry of Saxe-Lauenburg (1586-1665) had property interests in Ostrov, and her husband, Ottavio Piccolomini-Pieri, duca d’Amalfi (1599-1656) campaigned there. Established heading: Piccolomini, Maria Benigna Francisca 1635-1701 Other images of books from Maria Benigna Francisca Piccolomini's library. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 Sch615 539o All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut printer's device of Govaert Bac of Antwerp. Cf. Bac's entry in M. Harman, Printer's and Publisher's Devices in Incunabula in the University of Illinois Library (Urbana, Ill., 1983): The "bird cage" in this device is Bac's housemark, his address being "int vogelhuys." It is the device of his predecessor at this shop, Matthias van der Goes. Bac changed the initial, M, of Van der Goes, to his own initials, g b, and added his own mark, the good-luck symbol, 4, double-crossed and surmounted by a swastika. The shield bears the arms of the city of Antwerp, the two severed hands issuing from the central tower allegedly being derived from the practice of punishing pirates by cutting off their hands and throwing them into the Schelle. This is the third of several versions of this device, which was first used in 1496. Established form: Bac, Govaert Penn Libraries call number: GC5 Si116 505p All images from this book

photo.description: Folded woodcut map of Cerknisko Lake and environs, inserted into this work from the 1551 edition by Aquila of this work; cf. the reproduction in P. Simoniti, "The 1551 Herbenstein-Wernher Description of Lake Cerknica," Acta Carsologica 39.1 (2010), p. 150. Simoniti also contends that it is "highly likely that the motif for the woodcut of Lake Cerknica had been drawn by the famous Nürnberg painter, graphic artist and cartographer, Augustin Hirschvogel (1503-1553)" (p. 157). Penn's copy of De admirandis Hungariae aquis hypomnemation (1551), bought as part of the same transaction as this work (Chorographia Transylvaniae), wants the plate. Rudolf Hirsch conjectures that both of these works were disbound from a Sammelband owned by Sigismund von Herberstein, the dedicatee of De admirandis Hungariae aquis hypomnemation (cf. "Georg Wernher and Sigismund von Herberstein," Gutenberg Jahrbuch (1963), p. 121). Established form: Hirschvogel, Augustin, ‡d 1503-1553 Established form: Aquila, Aegidius, ‡d 1496-1552 Established form: Herberstein, Sigmund, ǂc Freiherr von, ǂd 1486-1566 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 R2714 550c All images from this book

photo.description: Illustrated armorial bookplate of Christian Ernst, Graf zu Stolberg-Wernigerode (1691-1771). According to E.A. Washburn, "Ex-Libris in a Medical Library", Bulletin of the Medical Library Association 27.4 (1939), p. 233, "Ernst's private library of 115,000 volumes, containing many medical books, was open to the public." Harvard University, in an online note describing its Stolberg Collection, elaborates: The golden age of the Stolberg library was during the reign of Christian Ernst (b. 1710-1771). He not only greatly increased its holdings and opened it to the public, but was also its librarian, commissioning the distinctive Stolberg bookplate and personally inscribing the publication date on the spine of each volume bound in white vellum. In 1746 Christian Ernst issued an edict making the collection—by then about 10,000 volumes—a public library. The Penn Libraries book in which this plate appears is indeed bound in pale parchment and has the imprint dates of its contents in ms. on the spine. Established heading (LC): Stolberg, Christian Ernst, ǂc Prinz, ǂd 1691-1771 Established heading: Fürstlich Stolberg-Wernigerodesche Bibliothek Penn Libraries call number: GC5 N1593 538t All images from this book

photo.description: Bookplate: Ex Musaeo Caroli Nodier. Bookplate of Charles Nodier (1780-1844), French Romantic author. He was briefly imprisoned in 1803 for an anti-Napoleonic skit. In 1824 he was appointed librarian of the Bibliothèque de l'Arsenal, Paris, where he presided over a notable literary salon. In 1833 he was elected to the Académie française. Another example of his bookplate can be seen here, in the provenance database of the Bibliothèque municipale de Lyon. photo.description: [Georg Friedrich Brandes (1709-1791) was a German jurist, overseer(?) of the University of Göttingen, and collector of books and art. The bulk of his notable library, some 22000 volumes, was sold in 1790 to Peter Friedrich Ludwig, Duke of Oldenburg (1755-1829) and formed the basis of the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg (founded 1792 and still in existence). Brandes also collected engravings and Michel Huber published a 2-volume catalog of the collection under the title Catalogue raisonné du cabinet d'estampes de feu Monsieur Brandes, secrétaire intime de la Chancellerie royale d'Hannovre (Leipzig: Rost, 1792-1794). These engravings appear to have been sold at auction in 1796. Two separate sales were planned: the first at Easter (18 April), comprising the English, German and Italian items; the second at Michaelmas (3 October), comprising items from France and the Netherlands. Cf. "Verkauf des Brandes'schen Kupferstich-Kabinets" in Neue Bibliothek der schönen Wissenschaften und der freyen Künste 56 (1795): 189-190, as well as the two sale catalogues: Premiere partie ou Écoles angloise, allemande et italienne, avec une grande collection de portraits: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de Pâques 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1795) and Seconde partie ou Écoles des Pays-Bas et Francoise: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de S. Michel 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1796). For more information on Brandes's library, including reproductions of his bookplate, see the online exhibition at the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg here, as well as G. Crusius, Aufklärung und Bibliophilie: Der Hannoveraner Sammler Georg Friedrich Brandes und seine Bibliothek (Heidelberg: Winter, 2008). Crusius also deals briefly with the engravings collection. Established form: Brandes, Georg Friedrich, ǂd 1709-1791.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 P6654 606t All images from this book

photo.description: Ex libri[s?] Andrea[e?] Martij. [The name is fairly common, but a "Dominus Andreas Martius Augustanus" is on the matriculation list of the University of Bologna for the year 1560; cf. E. Friedlaender and C. Malagola, eds., Acta Nationis Germanicae Universitatis Bononiensis ex archetypis tabularii Malvezziani (Berlin: G. Reimer, 1887), p. 338. This would be Andreas Mertz of Augsburg (d. 1603), son of Wilhelm Mertz (1467-1559) and his second wife Afra Rem (d. 1578); cf. E. Gebele, "Augsburg Bibliophilen," Zeitschrift des Historischen Vereins für Schwaben und Neuburg, Bd. 52 (1936), p. 54, note 110. According to G.C. Knod, Deutsche Studenten in Bologna (1289-1562) (Berlin: Decker, 1899), no. 2294, Mertz married Felicitas Welserin in 1562. (She was the daughter of Leonhard Welser and Sybille Hemmerlin and granddaughter of Bartholomeus Welser the Elder, Augsburg banker and privy counsellor of Charles V, who financed the conquest of Venezuela. Cf. Grosses vollständiges Universal-Lexicon aller Wissenschafften und Künste (Halle: J.H. Zedler, 1732-1750), entry Welser.) According to Gebele, Mertz possessed an extensive and comprehensive library whose catalog "findet sich noch in der Augsburger Stadtbibliothek (2o Cod. Aug. 381)" (p. 28). He thus seems a likely candidate for ownership of this book.] Ex hujus libera manu Joh. Pet. Caspari. 1697. [A "Johannes Petrus Casparus Wolffensis" [i.e. from Wolf an der Mosel, now a constituent of Traben-Trarbach in Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany) is named in the matriculation list of the philosophical faculty of the University of Strasbourg for 1689; cf. G.C. Knod, ed., Die Alten Matrikeln der Universität Strassburg, 1621 bis 1793 (Strassburg: K.J. Trübner, 1897-1902), Bd. 1, p. 380.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 M4804 565e All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Bookplate: Mrs. John V. L. Pruyn Born Harriet Corning Turner, in Troy, New York, 18 June 1822. Attended a fancy school for girls in New York City run by a French refugee from the revolution. In 1840 she married John Van Schaick Lansing Pruyn (1811-1877), an Albany lawyer and in the later part of his life the Chancellor of the University of the State of New York, which is New York's accreditation body. He served in the New York State Senate starting in 1861 and then did two stints as a Democrat in the US Congress from 1863-5 and 1867-9. She traveled extensively with her husband throughout Europe and the Near East, and took particular interest in sites of biblical or general religious interest. She died on March 22, 1859, and appears to have been fairly well known and respected in her circles for being an interesting and well-traveled character. Established heading: Pruyn, John V. L.,‏ ‎‡c Mrs.,‏ ‎‡d 1822-1859‏ Penn Libraries call number: AC8 Si262 862m Penn Libraries catalog record All images from this book
